Definition 3.1. We define a canonical isomorphism $f:FY=F(\mathcal{H}(X_{i}))\rightarrow F(\mathcal{H}(X_{i}^{\prime}))$ by induction on $Y$’s length as follows 1. If $Y$’s length is equal to 1, $Y=X_{\alpha}$ then $\displaystyle f=\widehat{F}:F0\rightarrow 0^{\prime}$ $\displaystyle\text{in case }X_{\alpha}=0$ $\displaystyle f=\acute{F}:F1\rightarrow 1^{\prime}$ $\displaystyle\text{in case }X_{\alpha}=1$ $\displaystyle f=id:FX_{\alpha}\rightarrow FX_{\alpha}$ in other cases 2. If $Y$’s length is more than 1, $Y=U_{1}\otimes U_{2}$ or $Y=U_{1}\oplus U_{2}.$ Then, the isomorphism $f$ is, respectively, the following compositions $\begin{CD}FY=F(U_{1}\otimes U_{2})@>{\widetilde{F}}>{}>FU_{1}\otimes FU_{2}@>{% f_{1}\otimes f_{2}}>{}>\mathcal{H}_{1}(X_{i}^{\prime})\otimes\mathcal{H}_{2}(X% _{i}^{\prime})\end{CD}$ $\begin{CD}FY=F(U_{1}\oplus U_{2})@>{\breve{F}}>{}>FU_{1}\oplus FU_{2}@>{f_{1}% \oplus f_{2}}>{}>\mathcal{H}_{1}(X_{i}^{\prime})\oplus\mathcal{H}_{2}(X_{i}^{% \prime})\end{CD}$ where $f_{1}$, $f_{2}$ are canonical isomorphisms determined by inductive supposition.
Definition 2.1. The canonical expansion form $h:Y\rightarrow\sum\limits_{I}A_{i}$ of $Y$ is defined as follows 1. If $Y=\sum\limits_{I}X_{i},$ $h=id:\sum\limits_{I}X_{i}\rightarrow\sum\limits_{I^{\prime}}X_{i}$, where $I$ is a subset of $\Omega$; whereas $I^{\prime}$ is the set of indexes $i$ such that $X_{i}\not=0$. 2. If $Y=U\otimes V,$ the isomorphism $h$ is the composition $\begin{CD}Y=U\otimes V@>{u\otimes v}>{}>(\sum\limits_{J}B_{j})\otimes(\sum% \limits_{T}C_{t})@>{F_{J,T}}>{}>\sum\limits_{J\times T}B_{j}C_{t}\end{CD}$ where $(u,\sum\limits_{J}B_{j})$, $(v,\sum\limits_{T}C_{t})$ are, respectively, canonical expansion forms of $U$, $V$ and defined by the induction supposition. 3. If $Y=U_{1}\oplus U_{2},$ $h$ is the composition $\begin{CD}Y=U_{1}\oplus U_{2}@>{u_{1}\oplus u_{2}}>{}>(\sum\limits_{I_{1}}B_{i% })\otimes(\sum\limits_{I_{2}}B_{i})@>{id}>{}>\sum\limits_{I^{\prime}}B_{i}\end% {CD}$ where $u_{1}$, $u_{2}$ are defined by the inductive supposition; $I=I_{1}\amalg I_{2}$; $i_{1}<i_{2}$ if $i_{1}\in I_{1},i_{2}\in I_{2}$ and $I^{\prime}$ is the set of indexes $i\in I$ such that $B_{i}\not=0$.
Definition 1.3. We define following isomorphisms $u_{I,J}:\sum\limits_{I}\sum_{J}(A_{i}\otimes B_{j})\longrightarrow\sum_{J}\sum% \limits_{I}(A_{i}\otimes B_{j})$ by induction on $|I|$ as follows 1. $u_{I,J}=id$ if $|I|\leq 1$ or $J=\emptyset$. 2. $u_{I,J}=\nu_{J}(u_{I^{\prime},J}\oplus id)$ if $|I|>1$. So, isomorphisms $u_{I,J}$ are also built from the isomorphisms $c,id$ by law $\oplus$ and these morphisms are functorial.
Definition 1.2. We define the isomorphism $\nu_{\sum A_{i},\sum B_{i}}:(\sum\limits_{I}A_{i})\oplus(\sum\limits_{I}B_{i})% \longrightarrow\sum\limits_{I}(A_{i}\oplus B_{i}),$ (which is abbreviated by $\nu_{I}$) by induction on $|I|$ as follows 1. $\nu_{I}=id$ if $|I|\leq 1$. 2. if $|I|>2,$ $\nu_{I}$ is defined by the folllowing commutative diagram $\begin{CD}(\sum\limits_{I}A_{i})\oplus(\sum\limits_{I}B_{i})@>{id}>{}>(\sum% \limits_{I^{\prime}}A_{i})\oplus A_{\alpha}\oplus(\sum\limits_{I^{\prime}}B_{i% })\oplus B_{\alpha}\\ @V{\nu_{I}}V{}V@V{}V{\nu}V\\ \sum\limits_{I}(A_{i}\oplus B_{i})@>{\nu_{I^{\prime}}\oplus id_{A_{\alpha}% \oplus B_{\alpha}}}>{}>(\sum\limits_{I^{\prime}}A_{i})\oplus(\sum\limits_{I^{% \prime}}B_{i})\oplus A_{\alpha}\oplus B_{\alpha}\end{CD}$ where $\nu=id\oplus c\oplus id$. We can see that the isomorphism $\nu_{I}$ is built only from isomorphisms $c,id$ by law $\oplus$. Moreover, the isomorphism $\nu_{I}$ is natural.
Definition 1.5. We define following isomorphisms $K_{I,J}:(\sum\limits_{I}A_{i})\otimes(\sum_{J}B_{j})\longrightarrow\sum\limits% _{J}\sum_{I}(A_{i}\otimes B_{j})$ as follows 1. $K_{I,J}=id$ if $I=\emptyset$. 2. $K_{I,J}=\widehat{L}^{X},$ where $X=\sum\limits_{I}A_{i}$ if $J=\emptyset$. 3. $K_{I,J}=f_{X},$ where $X=\sum\limits_{I}A_{i}$ in other cases.
Definition 2.1. Let $\mathcal{S}=(\Pi,A,\xi),\ \mathcal{S}^{\prime}=(\Pi^{\prime},A^{\prime},\xi^{% \prime})$ be Gr-categories. A functor $F:\mathcal{S}\to\mathcal{S}^{\prime}$ is called a functor of the type $(\varphi,f)$ if $F(x)=\varphi(x)\ \ ,\ \ F(x,u)=(\varphi(x),f(u))$ and $\varphi:\Pi\to\Pi^{\prime}$, $f:A\to A^{\prime}$ is a pair of group homomorphisms satisfying $f(xa)=\varphi(x)f(a)$ for $x\in\Pi,a\in A.$
Definition 2.2. If $F:(\Pi,A,\xi)\to(\Pi^{\prime},A^{\prime},\xi^{\prime})$ is a functor of the type $(\varphi,f),$ then $F$ induces 3-cocycles $\xi_{*}=f_{*}\xi,\xi^{\prime*}=\varphi^{*}\xi^{\prime},$ in which $\displaystyle(f_{*}\xi)(x,y,z)=f(\xi(x,y,z))$ $\displaystyle(\varphi^{*}\xi^{\prime})(x,y,z)=\xi^{\prime}(\varphi x,\varphi y% ,\varphi z)$ The function $k=\varphi^{\ast}\xi^{\prime}-f_{\ast}\xi$ is called an obstruction of the functor of the type $(\varphi,f).$
Definition 4.2 The State Space of ${\mathcal{D}}$ is a weighted digraph whose vertices are the elements of $k^{n}$ and there is an arrow going from the vertex $u$ to the vertex $v$ if there exists an update function $f_{i}\in S$, such that $v=f_{i}(u)$. The probability $p(u,v)$ of the arrow going from $u$ to $v$ is the sum of the probabilities $c_{f_{i}}$ of all functions $f_{i}$, such that $v=f_{i}(u)$, $u\hskip 7.227pt\frac{\hskip 7.227ptp(u,v)\hskip 7.227pt}{}>\hskip 7.227ptf_{i}% (u)=v$. We denote the State Space by $\mathcal{S_{D}}$.
Definition 7.1 (Equivalent PSN) If the morphism $h:\mathcal{D}_{1}\rightarrow\mathcal{D}_{2}$ satisfies that $\phi$, $h_{\phi}$ and $\mu$ are bijective functions, but the probabilities are not necessary equals, we say that ${\mathcal{D}}_{1}$, and ${\mathcal{D}}_{2}$ are equivalent PSN. We write ${\mathcal{D}}_{1}\simeq{\mathcal{D}}_{2}$.
Definition 5.1 (Morphisms of PSN) A morphism $h:{\mathcal{D}}_{1}\rightarrow{\mathcal{D}}_{2}$ consist of: (1) A graph morphism $\phi:\Delta\rightarrow\Gamma$, and a family of maps in the category Set, $(\widehat{\phi}_{b}:k_{\phi(b)}\rightarrow k_{b}\forall b\in\Delta),$ that induces the adjoint function $h_{\phi}$, see (1). (2) The induced adjoint map $h_{\phi}:k^{n}\rightarrow k^{m}$ holds that for all update functions $f$ in $S_{1}$ there exists an update function $g\in S_{2}$ such that $h$ is a SDS-morphism from $(\Gamma,(f:k^{n}\rightarrow k^{n}),\alpha_{j})$ to $(\Delta,(g:k^{m}\rightarrow k^{m}),\beta_{j})$. That is, the diagrams 2, 3, and 4 commute for all $f$ and its selected $g$. $h_{\phi}\circ f_{\alpha_{1}}\circ\cdots\circ f_{\alpha_{n}}=g_{\beta_{1}}\circ% \cdots\circ g_{\beta_{m}}\circ h_{\phi}$
Definition 4.1 A Probabilistic Sequential Network (PSN) ${\mathcal{D}}=(\Gamma,\{F_{a}\}_{a=1}^{|\Gamma|=n},(k_{a})_{a=1}^{n},(\alpha_{% j})_{j=1}^{m},C=\{c_{1},\ldots,c_{s}\})$ consists of: (1) a finite graph $\Gamma=(V_{\Gamma},E_{\Gamma})$ with $n$ vertices; (2) a family of finite sets $(k_{a}|a\in V_{\Gamma})$. (3) for each vertex $a$ of $\Gamma$ a set of local functions $F_{a}=\{f_{ai}:k^{n}\rightarrow k^{n}|1\leq i\leq\ell(i)\},$ is assigned. (i. e. there exists a bijection map $\sim:V_{\Gamma}\rightarrow\{F_{a}|1\leq a\leq n\}$) (for definition of local function see (2.1.2)). (4) a family of $m$ permutations $\alpha=(\alpha_{1}\hskip 7.227pt\ldots\hskip 7.227pt\alpha_{n})$ in the set of vertices $V_{\Gamma}$. (5) and a set $C=\{c_{1},\ldots,c_{s}\}$, of assign probabilities to $s$ update functions.
Definition 3.2. We say that a lattice $L$ is a pushdown lattice if the projection $(\,\cdot\,)_{0}:\mathbb{C}(L)\rTo L$ is a Grothendieck fibration.
Definition 5.3. For all $j,k\in J(L)$, we let: • $jAk$ if $j\neq k$ and, for some $m\in M(L)$, $j\uparrow m$ and $k\updownarrow m$, • $jBk$ if $j\neq k$ and, for some $m\in M(L)$, $j\updownarrow m$ and $k\downarrow m$, • $jCk$ if either $jAk$ or $jBk$.
Definition 5.9. A strict lower facet labelling of a lattice $L$ is a function $f:\mathbb{C}(L)\rTo\mathbb{N}$ such that $f(\gamma)=f(\delta)$ if $\delta\!\rightharpoondown\!\!\!\!\!\!{}^{\mbox{ }}\,\,\gamma$ and $f(\gamma)<f(\delta)$ if $\delta{\cal A}\gamma$. A strict upper facet labelling is defined dually: it is a function $f:\mathbb{C}(L)\rTo\mathbb{N}$ such that $f(\gamma)=f(\delta)$ if $\delta\!\rightharpoonup\!\!\!\!\!\!{}_{\mbox{ }}\,\,\gamma$ and $f(\gamma)<f(\delta)$ if $\delta{\cal B}\gamma$. A strict facet labelling of a lattice $L$ is a function $f:\mathbb{C}(L)\rTo\mathbb{N}$ which is both a strict lower facet labelling and a strict upper facet labelling.
Definition 5.2. For a lattice $L$ and $j,k\in J(L)$, we let $jDk$ if $j\neq k$ and there exists $m\in M(L)$ such that $j\uparrow m$ and $k\downarrow m$.
Definition 2.1. We say that a poset $P$ has pullbacks if every cospan in $P$ has a pullback. We say that $f:P\rTo Q$ preserves pullbacks if $f(u\land w)$ is the pullback of the cospan $(f(u),f(v),f(w))$, whenever $u\land w$ is the pullback of the cospan $(u,v,w)$.
Definition 5.6. For $\gamma,\delta\in\mathbb{C}(L)$, we let $\gamma{\cal A}\delta$ if there exists $\epsilon\in\mathbb{C}(L)$ and $u\in L$ such that $\epsilon\!\rightharpoondown\!\!\!\!\!\!{}^{u}\,\,\delta$ and $\delta_{1}\leq\gamma_{0}\prec\gamma_{1}\leq u$. The dual relation is defined as follows: $\gamma{\cal B}\delta$ if there exists $\epsilon\in\mathbb{C}(L)$ and $u\in L$ such that $\epsilon\!\rightharpoonup\!\!\!\!\!\!{}_{u}\,\,\delta$ and $u\leq\gamma_{0}\prec\gamma_{1}\leq\delta_{1}$.
Definition 2.1. Let ${\mathcal{M}}_{1}\xrightarrow{i}{\mathcal{N}}\xleftarrow{j}{\mathcal{M}}_{2}$ be a diagram in $P({\mathcal{C}},{\mathcal{G}rpd})$. The homotopy fiber product ${\mathcal{M}}_{1}\times^{h}_{{\mathcal{N}}}{\mathcal{M}}_{2}$, is the presheaf of groupoids defined as follows: 1. the objects of $({\mathcal{M}}_{1}\times^{h}_{{\mathcal{N}}}{\mathcal{M}}_{2})(X)$ are triples $(a,b,\phi)$ with $a\in{\mathcal{M}}_{1}(X),b\in{\mathcal{M}}_{2}(X)$ and an isomorphism $\phi:i(a)\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\sim}}{{\longrightarrow}}j(b)$, and 2. morphisms of $({\mathcal{M}}_{1}\times^{h}_{{\mathcal{N}}}{\mathcal{M}}_{2})(X)$ from $(a,b,\phi)$ to $(a^{\prime},b^{\prime},\phi^{\prime})$ are pairs $(\alpha,\beta)$ where $\alpha:a\cong a^{\prime}$ and $\beta:b\cong b^{\prime}$, such that $\phi^{\prime}\circ i(\alpha)=j(\beta)\circ\phi$.
Definition A.4. For ${\mathcal{M}}$ in $P({\mathcal{C}},{\mathcal{G}rpd})$ the site $Rep/{\mathcal{M}}$ has • Objects: strongly representable morphisms ${\mathcal{N}}\twoheadrightarrow{\mathcal{M}}$, • Morphisms from ${\mathcal{N}}_{1}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle f_{1}}}{{\longrightarrow}}{\mathcal{M}}$ to ${\mathcal{N}}_{2}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle f_{2}}}{{\longrightarrow}}{\mathcal{M}}$ consist of pairs $(g,\alpha)$ with $g:{\mathcal{N}}_{1}\rightarrow{\mathcal{N}}_{2}$ and $\alpha$ a homotopy $f_{1}\rightarrow f_{2}\circ g$. • Covers: collections of morphisms $\{{\mathcal{N}}_{i}\xrightarrow{u_{i}}{\mathcal{N}}\}$ such that the $u_{i}$ are strongly representable and for each $X\rightarrow{\mathcal{N}},X\in{\mathcal{C}}$ the collection $\{X\times_{{\mathcal{N}}}^{h}{\mathcal{N}}_{i}\rightarrow X\}$ is weakly equivalent to a cover in ${\mathcal{C}}$.
Definition 1.2. [H, Definition 5.6] A map $F\to G\in P({\mathcal{C}},{\mathcal{G}rpd})$ satisfies the local lifting conditions if 1. Given a commutative square $\parbox[c]{0.0pt}{ \xymatrix{ \emptyset\ar[r] \ar[d] & F(X) \ar[d] \lx@parboxnewline\star\ar[r] &% G(X)}}\hskip 11.381102pt\parbox[c]{0.0pt}{ \mbox{ $\Rightarrow$ $\exists$ % cover $U\rightarrow X$,} }\hskip 93.894094pt\parbox[c]{0.0pt}{ \xymatrix{\star\ar@/^3ex/@{-->}[rrr] \ar[d] & \emptyset\ar[l] \ar[r] \ar[d] & F(X) \ar[d] \ar[r] & F(U) \ar[d] \lx@parboxnewline\Delta^1 \ar@/_3ex/% @{-->}[rrr] & \star\ar[l] \ar[r] & G(X)\ar[r] & G(U).} }$ 2. For $A\rightarrow B$, one of the generating cofibrations $\partial\Delta^{1}\rightarrow\Delta^{1},\text{ }B\mathbb{Z}\rightarrow\star,$ given a commutative square $\parbox[c]{0.0pt}{ \xymatrix{ A \ar[r] \ar[d] & F(X) \ar[d] \lx@parboxnewline B \ar[r] & G(X)}}% \hskip 11.381102pt\parbox[c]{0.0pt}{ \mbox{ $\Rightarrow$ $\exists$ cover $U% \rightarrow X$,} }\hskip 93.894094pt\parbox[c]{0.0pt}{ \xymatrix{A \ar[r] \ar[d] & F(X) \ar[d] \ar[r] & F(U) \ar[d] \lx@parboxnewline B% \ar[r] \ar@{-->}[rru] & G(X) \ar[r] & G(U).} }$
Definition 4.2. We say that a topology on ${\mathcal{C}}$ is local if the notion of cover is local on the target. This means that if $\{U_{i}\to X\}$ is a cover and $\{V_{j}\to X\}$ is a collection of morphisms such that $\{V_{j}\times_{X}U_{i}\to U_{i}\}$ is a cover for each $i$ then $\{V_{k}\to X\}$ is also a cover.
Definition 3.6. Let $S$ be a scheme and let ${\mathcal{C}}$ be the category of $S$-schemes in the étale topology. A stack ${\mathcal{M}}$ is called a Deligne-Mumford (resp. algebraic) stack if the diagonal ${\mathcal{M}}\rightarrow{\mathcal{M}}\times{\mathcal{M}}$ is representable, separated and quasi-compact and if it admits an étale (resp. smooth) cover $X\rightarrow{\mathcal{M}}$ with $X\in{\mathcal{C}}$.
Definition 3.1. A morphism ${\mathcal{M}}\rightarrow{\mathcal{N}}\in P({\mathcal{C}},{\mathcal{G}rpd})$ is called • strongly representable if for each $X\in{\mathcal{C}}$ and each map $X\rightarrow{\mathcal{N}}$, the homotopy fiber product $X\times^{h}_{{\mathcal{N}}}{\mathcal{M}}$ is levelwise weakly equivalent to a representable presheaf. • representable if for each $X\in{\mathcal{C}}$ and each map $X\rightarrow{\mathcal{N}}$, the homotopy fiber product $X\times^{h}_{{\mathcal{N}}}{\mathcal{M}}$ is weakly equivalent to a representable presheaf.
Definition 3.7. Let ${\mathcal{C}}$ be a site. We say that ${\mathcal{M}}\in P({\mathcal{C}},{\mathcal{G}rpd})$ is generalized algebraic if its diagonal is representable and there is a cover $X\rightarrow{\mathcal{M}}$ with $X\in{\mathcal{C}}$.
Definition A.1. Let ${\mathcal{M}}$ be in $P({\mathcal{C}},{\mathcal{G}rpd})$ and let ${\mathcal{C}}/{\mathcal{M}}$ denote the site whose • objects are pairs $(X,f)$, where $X\in{\mathcal{C}}$ and $X\stackrel{{\scriptstyle f}}{{\longrightarrow}}{\mathcal{M}}$, • morphisms from $X\stackrel{{\scriptstyle f}}{{\longrightarrow}}{\mathcal{M}}$ to $X^{\prime}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle g}}{{\longrightarrow}}{\mathcal{M}}$ are pairs $(h,\alpha)$ where $X\stackrel{{\scriptstyle h}}{{\longrightarrow}}X^{\prime}$ and $\alpha$ is a homotopy $f\rightarrow g\circ h$, • covers are collections of morphisms which forget to covers in ${\mathcal{C}}$.
Definition 3.3. Let $P$ be a property of morphisms in ${\mathcal{C}}$ 2In the usual definition it is also required that $P$ is local on the target and stable under pullback (as in Definition 4.2). If $P$ is not stable under pullback then property $P$ for representable functors will be a stablized version of the origianl property. For our purposes neither of these extra requirement makes a difference.. We say $f\colon{\mathcal{M}}\to{\mathcal{N}}$ satisfies property P if for all maps $X\to{\mathcal{N}}$ with $X\in{\mathcal{C}}$, the map $X\times_{\mathcal{N}}^{h}{\mathcal{M}}\to X$ is weakly equivalent to a map in ${\mathcal{C}}$ which satisfies property P. Similarly, a collection $\{{\mathcal{U}}_{i}\to{\mathcal{N}}\}$ is a cover if for each $X\to{\mathcal{M}}$ with $X\in{\mathcal{C}}$, $\{{\mathcal{U}}_{i}\times^{h}_{{\mathcal{N}}}X\to X\}$ is weakly equivalent to a cover in ${\mathcal{C}}$.
Definition 4.1. Given a site ${\mathcal{C}}$ consider the presheaf of groupoids on ${\mathcal{C}}$ defined on objects by $X\mapsto iso({\mathcal{C}}/X)$ and on morphisms via pullback. We say that the site ${\mathcal{C}}$ satisfies descent for morphisms if this is a stack.
Definition 3.7. (see e.g. [S]) A Hopf algebra $A$ is called coconnected if every simple comodule over $A$ is trivial.
Definition 2.13. Let us say that an element of the tensor square5Since $G$ is a affine proalgebraic group, $\mathfrak{g}$ is a provector space. Thus tensor powers of $\mathfrak{g}$ will be understood in the completed sense. $\mathfrak{g}^{\otimes 2}$ is nilpotent if it projects to zero in $\mathfrak{g}_{r}^{\otimes 2}$, i.e., if $t\in\mathfrak{g}\otimes{\mathfrak{u}}+{\mathfrak{u}}\otimes\mathfrak{g}$.
Definition 2.6. Let us say that ${\mathcal{C}}$ is quasisymmetric if for every simple objects $X,Y\in{\mathcal{C}}$, one has $\beta^{2}={\rm Id}$ on $X\otimes Y$.
Definition 2.1. The tensor category $\mathcal{C}$ is called unipotent if the only simple object in $\mathcal{C}$ is the neutral object ${\bf 1}$.
Definition 3.1. Let us say that a fiber functor $F:{\mathcal{C}}\to\text{Vec}$ is unipotent if it coincides with the standard one on the subcategory ${\mathcal{C}}_{s}=\text{Rep}(G_{\rm red},u)$.
Definition 2.9. We will call ${\mathcal{C}}_{s}$ the canonical symmetric part of ${\mathcal{C}}$.
Definition 2.5. We will call the supergroup $G_{\rm red}$ the reductive quotient of $G$, and $U$ the unipotent radical of $G$. We will say that a supergroup $G$ is reductive if $U=1$ and $G=G_{\rm red}$.
Definition 4.11. If $Y$ is a simplicial set and $y\in Y_{0}$ is a vertex, let $(Y,y)$ denote the based simplicial set we get by considering $y$ as the base vertex of $Y$. $P(Y,y)$ is then the simplicial set with $P(Y,y)_{n}=\{z\colon\Delta[n+1]\to Y\mid z(0)=y\}.$ If $p\colon X\to Y$ is a map of simplicial sets and $y\in Y_{0}$ is a vertex, we define $P(p,y)$, the (right) homotopy fiber over $y$, to be the pullback in the following diagram: $\xymatrix{P(p,y)\ar[r]\ar[d]_{\bar{p}}&X\ar[d]^{p}\\ P(Y,y)\ar[r]_{\bar{\jmath}}&Y}$
Definition 4.1. Let $J_{r}=\{\Lambda^{k}[{n}]\to\Delta[n]\mid n\geq 1\text{ and }0<k\leq n\}$. A map of simplicial sets $p\colon X\to Y$ is a right fibration if it has the right lifting property (RLP) with respect to $J_{r}$ (i.e., is in $J_{r}$-inj, using the notation of [Hov99]). A map $i\colon A\to B$ is a right anodyne extension if it has the left lifting property (LLP) with respect to all right fibrations (i.e., is in $J_{r}$-cof).
Definition 5.1. Let $\phi\colon X\to N{\mathcal{O}}$ and $\psi\colon Y\to N{\mathcal{O}}$ be simplicial sets over $N{\mathcal{O}}$, and let $f\colon X\to Y$ be a map over $N{\mathcal{O}}$. (1) Say that $f$ is a weak equivalence over $N{\mathcal{O}}$ if, for each vertex $b\in N{\mathcal{O}}$, $(F\phi)(b)\to(F\psi)(b)$ is a weak equivalence of simplicial sets. (2) Say that $f$ is a cofibration over $N{\mathcal{O}}$ if it is a cofibration of simplicial sets, i.e., an inclusion. (3) Say that $f$ is a fibration over $N{\mathcal{O}}$ if it is a right fibration and if, for each vertex $b\in N{\mathcal{O}}$, $\phi^{-1}(b)\to\psi^{-1}(b)$ is a fibration of simplicial sets.
Definition 4.6. Let $C\Delta\colon\Delta^{-}\to{\mathcal{S}}_{*}$ be the covariant functor with $C\Delta[n]=\Delta[n+1]$ with $0$ as the base vertex. If $f\colon[m]\to[n]$, let $\bar{f}\colon[m+1]\to[n+1]$ be the function defined by $\bar{f}(0)=0$ and $\bar{f}(k)=f(k-1)+1$ for $k>0$; let $C\Delta(f)=\bar{f}^{*}$. Now extend $C$ to a functor $C\colon{\mathcal{S}}\to{\mathcal{S}}_{*}$ by letting $CA=\int^{n\in\Delta^{-}}\!\!\!\!A_{n}\times C\Delta[n].$
Definition 2.3. Regions $A$ and $B$ in a causal site are disjoint if the only region which is contained in both $A$ and $B$ is the empty region. More generally, a set of regions is disjoint if each pair of regions it contains is disjoint.
Definition 7.1. If $A$ is a region in a causal site, the bisimplicial set of regions contained in it is its bisimplicial patch. This bisimplicial set sits naturally inside the elementary classifying space (Definition 5.1).
Definition 2.14. A causal site is Noetherian if every chain of strict descending regions $A_{1}\supset A_{2}\supset A_{3}\supset\cdots$ is finite. It is locally Noetherian if every local site is Noetherian.
Definition 8.2. We call this weak 2-functor the tangent 2-bundle of the causal site.
Definition 5.3. The physical classifying space of a causal site is the bisimplicial set whose $(m,n)$-bisimplices correspond to the following data: a) a sequence $A_{0},\ldots,A_{m}$ of regions with $A_{i}\prec A_{i+1}$; b) for each $i=0,\ldots,m-1$ and $j=0,\ldots,n$ a causal path $C^{j}_{i}$ from $A_{i}$ to $A_{i+1}$; such that for each $i$ and $j$, the causal path $C^{j}_{i}$ is a refinement of $C^{j+1}_{i}$. The two types of face maps are given by composition of rows and columns respectively.
Definition 2.11. For regions $A$ and $B$ with $A\prec B$, we say that $C$ is strongly complete for $A$ and $B$ if for all non-empty $A^{\prime}\subseteq A$ and $B^{\prime}\subseteq B$, any causal path from $A^{\prime}$ to $B^{\prime}$ can refined to a causal path from $A^{\prime}$ to $B^{\prime}$ one of whose members is contained in $C$.
Definition 7.3. A region $R$ is an $n$-ball if it is contained in a region $R^{\prime}$ such that the relative homotopy type is that of an $n$-sphere. A causal site is a grained $n$-manifold if every region is contained in a union of a finite number of $n$-balls.
Definition 5.1. The bisimplicial set associated to a causal site above is called its elementary classifying space.
Definition 2.10. For regions $A$ and $B$, write $A\precsim B$ if there exist non-empty subsets $A^{\prime}\subseteq A$ and $B^{\prime}\subseteq B$ with $A^{\prime}\prec B^{\prime}$ or $A^{\prime}=B^{\prime}$. We say that $A$ weakly precedes $B$.
Definition 2.16. If $A$ and $B$ are regions in a causal site, we say that $A$ is amply pointed with respect to $B$ if $A\prec B$ and if $C,D\subseteq A$ then either $C$ or $D$ contains a relative point for $B$ which the other does not, or $C=D$. A causal site is amply pointed if all causal pairs in it are.
Definition 2.4. Suppose $S$ and $T$ are sets of disjoint regions. If every region in $S$ contains some region in $T$, we say that $T$ is a refinement of $S$. That is, $T$ is obtained from $S$ by shrinking some regions and adding new regions. A causal path $P$ is a sequence $A_{1}\prec A_{2}\prec\cdots\prec A_{m}$ of non-empty regions. If $A\prec A_{1}$ and $A_{m}\prec B$, we say that $P$ is a causal path from $A$ to $B$ and has length $m+1$. There is exactly one causal path of length $1$. A refinement of the causal path $A_{1}\prec A_{2}\prec\cdots\prec A_{m}$ is a causal path $C_{1}\prec C_{2}\prec\cdots\prec C_{n}$ such that $\{C_{j}\}$ is a refinement of $\{A_{i}\}$.
Definition 2.2. A causal site is a set of “regions” with two binary relations denoted $\subseteq$ and $\prec$ satisfying the axioms below. If $A\subseteq B$ we say that $A$ is a subset of $B$ or that $B$ contains $A$. If $A\prec B$ we say that $A$ precedes $B$. 1. $\subseteq$ is a partial order on the set of regions. This means that for all regions $A$, $B$ and $C$: a) $A\subseteq B$ and $B\subseteq C$ implies $A\subseteq C$; b) $A\subseteq A$; c) $A\subseteq B$ and $B\subseteq A$ implies $A=B$. 2. The partial order $\subseteq$ has a minimum element $\phi$. This means that $\phi$ is contained in every region $A$. This uniquely determines $\phi$, and $\phi$ is called the empty region. 3. The partial order $\subseteq$ has unions. This means that for all regions $A$ and $B$, there exists a region $A\cup B$ such that: a) $A\subseteq A\cup B$ and $B\subseteq A\cup B$; b) if $A\subseteq C$ and $B\subseteq C$ then $A\cup B\subseteq C$. These requirements uniquely determine $A\cup B$, and the binary operation $\cup$ is automatically associative and commutative. 4. $\prec$ induces a strict partial order on the non-empty regions. This means that for all non-empty regions $A$, $B$ and $C$: a) $A\prec B$ and $B\prec C$ implies $A\prec C$; b) $A$ does not precede $A$. 5. For all regions $A$, $B$ and $C$, $A\subseteq B$ and $B\prec C$ implies $A\prec C$. 6. For all regions $A$, $B$ and $C$, $A\subseteq B$ and $C\prec B$ implies $C\prec A$. 7. For all regions $A$, $B$ and $C$, $A\prec C$ and $B\prec C$ implies $A\cup B\prec C$. 8. For all regions $A$ and $B$, there exists a region $B_{A}$ such that: a) $B_{A}\prec A$ and $B_{A}\subseteq B$; b) if $D\prec A$ and $D\subseteq B$ then $D\subseteq B_{A}$. These requirements uniquely determine $B_{A}$, and $B_{A}$ is called the cutting of $A$ by $B$. Note that $B_{A}$ can be empty. 9. If $A$ and $C$ are non-empty regions such that $A\prec C$ and there exists a $D$ with $A\prec D\prec C$, then there exists a $B$ complete with respect to $A\prec C$. The definition of “complete” is below (Definition 2.5).
